20
00:01:46,507 --> 00:01:49,041
    ♪ Let me hold your hand ♪   

21
00:01:49,109 --> 00:01:51,543
    ♪ And try to understand ♪   

22
00:01:51,612 --> 00:01:54,146
   ♪ I want a girl like you ♪   

23
00:01:54,215 --> 00:01:56,682
     ♪ Tell my trouble to ♪     

24
00:01:56,750 --> 00:01:59,117
       ♪ Don't be afraid ♪      

25
00:01:59,186 --> 00:02:00,919
  ♪ You've heard what I said ♪  

26
00:02:00,988 --> 00:02:02,721
           MAN: Fats,           
    how'd this rock 'n' roll    

27
00:02:02,790 --> 00:02:04,189
    all get started, anyway?    

28
00:02:04,258 --> 00:02:05,324
      -Well, what they call     
          rock 'n' roll         

29
00:02:05,392 --> 00:02:06,758
    now is rhythm and blues.    

30
00:02:06,827 --> 00:02:08,160
        I've been playin'       
  for 15 years in New Orleans.  

31
00:02:08,229 --> 00:02:11,663
     ♪ I love you the best ♪    

32
00:02:11,732 --> 00:02:13,532
   ♪ Let the four winds blow ♪  

33
00:02:13,601 --> 00:02:16,501
     -NARRATOR: A native son    
   of New Orleans, Fats Domino  

34
00:02:16,570 --> 00:02:18,737
would pioneer the big beat sound

35
00:02:18,806 --> 00:02:22,641
  and become one of the world's 
   most beloved entertainers.   

36
00:02:22,710 --> 00:02:24,643
         [Instrumental]         

37
00:02:40,661 --> 00:02:47,065
      Antoine Domino, Jr.,      
  arrived on February 26, 1928, 

38
00:02:47,134 --> 00:02:48,934
     delivered by a midwife     

39
00:02:49,003 --> 00:02:51,703
       with the assistance      
 of his grandmother, Carmelite, 

40
00:02:51,772 --> 00:02:54,406
 who had been born into slavery.

41
00:02:54,475 --> 00:02:59,511
    Antoine Jr. was the last    
    of eight Domino children    

42
00:02:59,580 --> 00:03:02,514
   and the only one to be born  
         in New Orleans.        

43
00:03:06,887 --> 00:03:08,487
  -MAN: The -- the neighborhood 

44
00:03:08,555 --> 00:03:11,957
   that Fats Domino grew up in  
 is called the Lower Ninth Ward 

45
00:03:12,026 --> 00:03:13,792
         in New Orleans.        

46
00:03:13,861 --> 00:03:16,895
  And it's arguably where a lot 
of the best musicians came from.

47
00:03:16,964 --> 00:03:18,230
   And it's a part of the city  

48
00:03:18,298 --> 00:03:21,299
    that enjoys a reputation    
   in New Orleans for being...  

49
00:03:21,368 --> 00:03:23,301
That's the -- the heart, really,

50
00:03:23,370 --> 00:03:25,504
   the heartbeat of the city.   

51
00:03:25,572 --> 00:03:28,740
       -MAN: It was almost      
        like another, uh,       

52
00:03:28,809 --> 00:03:31,443
   world, like another world.   

53
00:03:31,512 --> 00:03:32,911
 There was always talk about... 

54
00:03:32,980 --> 00:03:35,781
         When you talked        
   about the Lower Ninth Ward,  

55
00:03:35,849 --> 00:03:39,084
    you talk as if the people   
      who lived down there      

56
00:03:39,153 --> 00:03:42,087
  didn't have as much goin' on  
     as the people mid-city.    

57
00:03:42,156 --> 00:03:43,355
  Of course, some of the people 

58
00:03:43,424 --> 00:03:48,627
 who lived down there had a lot 
            goin' on.           

59
00:03:48,695 --> 00:03:52,264
       -DOMINO: I was born      
   on Jourdan Avenue down here  

60
00:03:52,332 --> 00:03:54,800
       in the Ninth Ward.       

61
00:03:54,868 --> 00:03:58,804
 They said I was born in a house
     at 1939 Jourdan Avenue.    

62
00:04:02,810 --> 00:04:04,176
           Thank you.           

63
00:04:04,244 --> 00:04:05,477
      Thank you very much.      

64
00:04:05,546 --> 00:04:08,013
       I went to a school       
   right down the street here.  

65
00:04:08,081 --> 00:04:13,084
     It was about 10 blocks     
   from here, McCartey School.  

66
00:04:13,153 --> 00:04:14,886
    And then I remember years   
       ago when I used --       

67
00:04:14,955 --> 00:04:17,722
 used to come home from school. 

68
00:04:17,791 --> 00:04:21,526
 My mom used to be cooking, um, 
        on a wood stove.        

69
00:04:21,595 --> 00:04:24,663
         And sometimes I        
      got from school, uh,      

70
00:04:24,731 --> 00:04:26,998
      and I had to cut wood     
          that evening.         

71
00:04:27,067 --> 00:04:28,867
    Another thing I remember    
 when I lived on Jourdan Avenue,

72
00:04:28,936 --> 00:04:33,405
 I used to pick iron and copper 
 in the street, Jourdan Avenue, 

73
00:04:33,474 --> 00:04:34,840
       I used to live on.       

74
00:04:34,908 --> 00:04:36,374
     The street was so bad,     
      the holes were so big     

75
00:04:36,443 --> 00:04:39,444
     they used to get stuff     
   from the cotton bale and --  

76
00:04:39,513 --> 00:04:42,080
   and and fill the street up   
 with nothin' but tin and iron. 

77
00:04:42,149 --> 00:04:44,716
     That -- that's the way     
       Jourdan Avenue was.      

78
00:04:44,785 --> 00:04:46,551
      And I used to sell it     
      to -- sell the scrap.     

79
00:04:46,620 --> 00:04:49,721
    If you made your 20 cents   
      or 25 cents livin'...     

80
00:04:49,790 --> 00:04:53,058
    That was a lot of money,    
     25 cents, in that time.    

81
00:04:53,126 --> 00:04:54,659
        -When he got out        
       and about, he was,       

82
00:04:54,728 --> 00:04:56,795
     uh, roamin' the streets    
       of the Ninth Ward.       

83
00:04:56,864 --> 00:04:59,831
  And he would love to pick up  
      things that he'd see.     

84
00:04:59,900 --> 00:05:02,067
   And sometimes he'd sell 'em  
       to the junkman who,      

85
00:05:02,135 --> 00:05:03,368
         uh, ironically,        

86
00:05:03,437 --> 00:05:06,304
        would become part       
of the song "The Junker's Blues"

87
00:05:06,373 --> 00:05:07,806
     that he'd later record.    

88
00:05:07,875 --> 00:05:09,541
His life was changed, basically,

89
00:05:09,610 --> 00:05:11,376
         when his sister        
    married Harrison Verrett,   

90
00:05:11,445 --> 00:05:15,113
    who was a, uh, relatively   
 well-known New Orleans musician

91
00:05:15,182 --> 00:05:16,715
        who played banjo.       

92
00:05:16,783 --> 00:05:22,654
               ♪♪               

93
00:05:22,723 --> 00:05:23,655
   -DOMINO: My brother-in-law   
      Harrison used to play     

94
00:05:23,724 --> 00:05:25,190
    with Papa Celestin Band.    

95
00:05:25,259 --> 00:05:28,493
   You know, and, uh, one time  
  I went to the French Quarter, 

96
00:05:28,562 --> 00:05:30,862
    and I heard them play out   
      there several times.      

97
00:05:30,931 --> 00:05:33,732
  That's where I really learned 
     from my brother-in-law,    

98
00:05:33,800 --> 00:05:35,233
        Harrison Verrett.       

99
00:05:35,302 --> 00:05:36,701
    He had a lot of patience.   
        He would take...        

100
00:05:36,770 --> 00:05:38,436
    He -- he just loved bein'   
    with children, you know?    

101
00:05:38,505 --> 00:05:41,306
           And that's           
     what I loved about him.    

102
00:05:41,375 --> 00:05:43,742
-COLEMAN: Fats had always played
   around on the family piano   

103
00:05:43,810 --> 00:05:45,176
    since they had bought it.   

104
00:05:45,245 --> 00:05:46,845
          First of all,         
  they put it out in the garage 

105
00:05:46,913 --> 00:05:49,414
      to keep him from, uh,     
drivin' them crazy a little bit.

106
00:05:49,483 --> 00:05:51,016
     But he even quit school    

107
00:05:51,084 --> 00:05:52,617
        because he wanted       
   to play the piano so much.   

108
00:05:52,686 --> 00:05:55,620
    And, uh, so he only went    
      to the fourth grade.      

109
00:05:55,689 --> 00:05:58,290
  Harrison actually taught him  
         how to play it.        

110
00:05:58,358 --> 00:06:01,159
      And he put the notes      
 on the piano on pieces of tape.

111
00:06:01,228 --> 00:06:02,894
   And it was a beat-up piano.  

112
00:06:02,963 --> 00:06:05,897
You could actually see the metal
    through the -- the ivory.   

113
00:06:05,966 --> 00:06:09,367
    But, uh, Fats, you know,    
    got some sound out of it.   

114
00:06:09,436 --> 00:06:11,102
-DOMINO: We had an upright piano
          in the house.         

115
00:06:11,171 --> 00:06:13,772
    He'd teach me the chords,   
         the foundation.        

116
00:06:13,840 --> 00:06:14,873
           If you know          
     how to play the chord,     

117
00:06:14,941 --> 00:06:16,274
      he'd write the chord      
          down to you.          

118
00:06:16,343 --> 00:06:18,209
 And you play this famous song, 
      playin' in the band,      

119
00:06:18,278 --> 00:06:19,744
       just by the chord.       

120
00:06:19,813 --> 00:06:23,915
 And after I learnt that, that's
   when I just went on my own.  

121
00:06:23,984 --> 00:06:25,617
     Everybody had a piano.     

122
00:06:25,686 --> 00:06:27,318
         I used to stop.        

123
00:06:27,387 --> 00:06:30,321
  And the -- the manager said,  
       "Where's Fats at?"       

124
00:06:30,390 --> 00:06:31,890
      His son would say...      
       His son was Willie.      

125
00:06:31,958 --> 00:06:33,324
  Willie'd say, "I don't know." 

126
00:06:33,393 --> 00:06:34,759
           Say, "Well,          
   you got a piano over there.  

127
00:06:34,828 --> 00:06:36,127
 You better go look. He might be
    where you left the piano.   

128
00:06:36,196 --> 00:06:38,630
       Where the piano at,      
         where Fats at."        

129
00:06:38,699 --> 00:06:41,900
     -COLEMAN: From the late    
        '30s to the '40s,       

130
00:06:41,968 --> 00:06:45,503
     Fats started listening     
       more to jukeboxes.       

131
00:06:45,572 --> 00:06:48,573
  That's basically the way that 
blacks heard music in those days

132
00:06:48,642 --> 00:06:51,443
    because not a lot of 'em    
       had record players.      

133
00:06:51,511 --> 00:06:55,313
     There was no radio that    
played black music at that time.

134
00:06:55,382 --> 00:07:00,718
     [Upbeat music playing]     

135
00:07:00,787 --> 00:07:03,188
  Fats' primary love for music  

136
00:07:03,256 --> 00:07:05,457
    was in the boogie-woogie    
         piano players.         

137
00:07:08,528 --> 00:07:10,328
      He always listened to     
         Meade Lux Lewis        

138
00:07:10,397 --> 00:07:13,598
        and Pete Johnson,       
    the great piano players.    

139
00:07:15,502 --> 00:07:17,268
   His cousins had a, uh, bar.  

140
00:07:17,337 --> 00:07:19,337
    And he actually not only    
      had a jukebox there,      

141
00:07:19,406 --> 00:07:21,139
 he also had a sounding machine,

142
00:07:21,208 --> 00:07:23,842
     which was I guess kind     
   of a luxury in those days.   

143
00:07:23,910 --> 00:07:25,610
             The one            
   he particularly remembered,  

144
00:07:25,679 --> 00:07:28,179
     I think it was a video     
      called Low Down Dog.      

145
00:07:28,248 --> 00:07:31,116
   It was actually a comedian   
     who was found his woman    

146
00:07:31,184 --> 00:07:33,118
  foolin' around with different 
    guy in the kitchen, okay,   

147
00:07:33,186 --> 00:07:34,319
    and somethin' like that.    

148
00:07:34,387 --> 00:07:35,820
    And he -- he chased her.    

149
00:07:35,889 --> 00:07:37,489
      And he -- he started      
       singin' this song,       

150
00:07:37,557 --> 00:07:39,190
       pointin' his finger      
         at her sayin',         

151
00:07:39,259 --> 00:07:41,326
     "I ain't gonna be your     
     low-down dog no more."     

152
00:07:41,394 --> 00:07:46,698
    -♪ I ain't gonna be your    
     low-down dog no more ♪     

153
00:07:46,766 --> 00:07:48,166
        ♪ Ain't gonna be        
   your low-down dog no more ♪  

154
00:07:48,235 --> 00:07:49,801
  -COLEMAN: People that knew it 
   at the time was Joe Turner   

155
00:07:49,870 --> 00:07:52,971
        who was singin'.        
  He was just mimin' the song.  

156
00:07:53,039 --> 00:07:56,508
  And was Pete Johnson who was  
playin' the boogie-woogie piano.

157
00:07:56,576 --> 00:07:59,944
        -♪ Work all day,        
    don't you know, my babe ♪   

158
00:08:00,013 --> 00:08:01,779
     -Fats loved that video.    

159
00:08:01,848 --> 00:08:03,882
 And he actually started playing
         "Low Down Dog."        

160
00:08:03,950 --> 00:08:06,217
     And he kept playin' it     
  for the next half a century.  

161
00:08:06,286 --> 00:08:10,288
               ♪♪               

162
00:08:10,357 --> 00:08:14,659
          -♪ Ooh wee ♪          

163
00:08:14,728 --> 00:08:19,130
         ♪ Oo-ooh wee ♪         

164
00:08:19,199 --> 00:08:20,932
  ♪ It's a low down shame... ♪  

165
00:08:21,001 --> 00:08:23,468
     CLEARY: It's very hard     
           to find out          

166
00:08:23,537 --> 00:08:27,005
       what his formative       
         influences are.        

167
00:08:27,073 --> 00:08:29,707
          Basic blues,          
     old-style blues piano.     

168
00:08:29,776 --> 00:08:30,942
       It's -- and it's --      

169
00:08:31,011 --> 00:08:33,978
And boogie-woogie, I mean, that,
        you know, that --       

170
00:09:16,122 --> 00:09:18,389
   Straight-up boogie-woogie.   

171
00:09:18,458 --> 00:09:22,060
      -♪ Bad, bad whiskey ♪     

172
00:09:22,128 --> 00:09:25,663
      ♪ Bad, bad whiskey ♪      

173
00:09:25,732 --> 00:09:31,936
       ♪ Bad, bad whiskey       
  made me lose my happy home ♪  

174
00:09:32,005 --> 00:09:33,538
   -COLEMAN: Another favorite   
       performer of Fats'       

175
00:09:33,606 --> 00:09:37,108
    was Amos Milburn, who was   
  a great boogie-woogie player. 

176
00:09:37,177 --> 00:09:39,243
        Amos played these       
         low-down blues.        

177
00:09:39,312 --> 00:09:42,947
 And they were all really sexy. 

178
00:09:43,016 --> 00:09:47,985
        Fats played blues       
       like Amos Milburn.       

179
00:09:58,965 --> 00:10:02,366
   Another influence of Fats'   
        was Louis Jordan,       

180
00:10:02,435 --> 00:10:05,470
    who was the most popular    
     black singer-performer     

181
00:10:05,538 --> 00:10:07,238
          of the 1940s.         

182
00:10:07,307 --> 00:10:11,008
        And he was famous       
  for all of his novelty songs. 

183
00:10:11,077 --> 00:10:13,077
     But more significantly,    

184
00:10:13,146 --> 00:10:14,946
        he did some songs       

185
00:10:15,014 --> 00:10:17,248
  that I would almost consider  
    rockers, like "Caldonia."   

186
00:10:17,317 --> 00:10:20,251
               ♪♪               

187
00:10:20,320 --> 00:10:21,385
    -♪ Walkin' with my baby ♪   

188
00:10:21,454 --> 00:10:22,987
   ♪ She got great, big feet ♪  

189
00:10:23,056 --> 00:10:24,222
 ♪ She's long, lean and lanky ♪ 

190
00:10:24,290 --> 00:10:25,323
         ♪ And ain't had        
        nothin' to eat ♪        

191
00:10:25,391 --> 00:10:27,191
      ♪ But she's my baby ♪     

192
00:10:27,260 --> 00:10:31,028
♪ And I love her just the same ♪

193
00:10:31,097 --> 00:10:32,463
   ♪ Crazy about that woman ♪   

194
00:10:32,532 --> 00:10:35,900
 ♪ 'Cause Caldonia is her name ♪

195
00:10:35,969 --> 00:10:37,602
    -COLEMAN: He's shouting.    

196
00:10:37,670 --> 00:10:42,306
  And he's -- and he's playing  
 this heavy boogie-woogie beat. 

197
00:10:42,375 --> 00:10:45,376
   And so that was a song that  
 almost everybody in New Orleans

198
00:10:45,445 --> 00:10:46,777
 played at one time or another. 

199
00:10:46,846 --> 00:10:49,247
-♪ I've always loved you, baby ♪

200
00:10:49,315 --> 00:10:52,483
♪ 'Cause Caldonia is your name ♪

201
00:11:04,998 --> 00:11:07,798
      -COLEMAN: After Fats      
  started playing in the little 

202
00:11:07,867 --> 00:11:09,066
        Ninth Ward clubs,       

203
00:11:09,135 --> 00:11:11,202
       he started running       
      into different people     

204
00:11:11,271 --> 00:11:14,772
    who would be influential    
         in his career.         

205
00:11:14,841 --> 00:11:17,975
   The first one was probably   
         Billy Diamond,         

206
00:11:18,044 --> 00:11:19,777
  who was a local band leader.  

207
00:11:19,846 --> 00:11:21,045
      He was a bass player.     

208
00:11:21,114 --> 00:11:22,914
He was a little short go-getter.

209
00:11:22,982 --> 00:11:24,815
 Fats told me during those days,

210
00:11:24,884 --> 00:11:27,518
   Billy Diamond was the only   
  person who could find a gig.  

211
00:11:27,587 --> 00:11:29,820
     Uh, he could find a gig    
     when nobody else could.    

212
00:11:29,889 --> 00:11:32,590
           -I gave him          
   the name Fats before then,   

213
00:11:32,659 --> 00:11:34,759
  before he even had a record.  

214
00:11:34,827 --> 00:11:36,127
    I gave him the name Fats    

215
00:11:36,195 --> 00:11:38,262
  after a guy named Fat Waller  
       back in them days.       

216
00:11:38,331 --> 00:11:41,065
  He was a great piano player.  

217
00:11:41,134 --> 00:11:44,669
 He got mad when I played piano,
         called him fat.        

218
00:11:44,737 --> 00:11:46,871
       "Don't call me fat.      
  Don't call me fat, brown boy. 

219
00:11:46,940 --> 00:11:48,573
          I don't know          
  what you callin' me fat for.  

220
00:11:48,641 --> 00:11:51,809
  I don't call you Fat Billy."  

221
00:11:51,878 --> 00:11:54,145
      -NARRATOR: While Fats     
 was pounding out boogie-woogie 

222
00:11:54,213 --> 00:11:56,647
    with Billy Diamond's Band   
         at the Hideaway        

223
00:11:56,716 --> 00:11:58,749
  and other neighborhood clubs, 

224
00:11:58,818 --> 00:12:02,687
 a New Orleans trumpet sensation
 by the name of Dave Bartholomew

225
00:12:02,755 --> 00:12:04,922
         was on a roll.         

226
00:12:04,991 --> 00:12:07,992
   -COLEMAN: Dave Bartholomew   
  was one of the most popular,  

227
00:12:08,061 --> 00:12:10,962
    if not the most popular,    
    band leader in the city.    

228
00:12:11,030 --> 00:12:13,431
   And occasionally Fats went   
 and see him and check him out. 

229
00:12:13,499 --> 00:12:14,999
    Earl Palmer, who was, uh,   

230
00:12:15,068 --> 00:12:19,537
      Dave's great drummer,     
    had him sit in one time.    

231
00:12:19,605 --> 00:12:21,405
        Fats got up there       
   and played that little jam   

232
00:12:21,474 --> 00:12:23,107
       and boogie-woogie,       
     "Swanee River Boogie,"     

233
00:12:23,176 --> 00:12:26,410
       or whatever it was,      
 and maybe another song or two. 

234
00:12:26,479 --> 00:12:28,245
        Dave Bartholomew        
       did not like that.       

235
00:12:28,314 --> 00:12:29,780
      As a matter of fact,      
    he came up to Earl Palmer   

236
00:12:29,849 --> 00:12:31,148
      and said afterwards,      

237
00:12:31,217 --> 00:12:33,117
      "I thought I told you     
  not to let that guy sit in."  

238
00:12:33,186 --> 00:12:34,785
    Of course, he had no clue   

239
00:12:34,854 --> 00:12:39,056
      that they would have      
  a incredible history to come, 

240
00:12:39,125 --> 00:12:41,892
      as far as making some     
 of the most influential records

241
00:12:41,961 --> 00:12:45,696
   in the next 10 or 15 years.  

242
00:12:45,765 --> 00:12:47,631
      -NARRATOR: One night,     
    Bartholomew brought a man   

243
00:12:47,700 --> 00:12:50,768
     from Imperial Records,     
        a Mr. Lew Chudd,        

244
00:12:50,837 --> 00:12:53,471
       to see Fats perform      
        at a local club.        

245
00:12:53,539 --> 00:12:56,374
-DOMINO: I work at the Hideaway.

246
00:12:56,442 --> 00:12:59,243
        I was real famous       
at the Hideaway for just playin'

247
00:12:59,312 --> 00:13:02,346
      other people number.      

248
00:13:02,415 --> 00:13:04,715
       Dave and Lew Chudd       
   came down there one night.   

249
00:13:04,784 --> 00:13:06,851
    Lew Chudd wanted to hear    
        me sing and play.       

250
00:13:06,919 --> 00:13:09,086
            So I did.           

251
00:13:09,155 --> 00:13:11,622
      -COLEMAN: Fats played     
      "The Junker's Blues."     

252
00:13:11,691 --> 00:13:14,658
          -♪ They call,         
     they call me a junker ♪    

253
00:13:14,727 --> 00:13:18,262
 -COLEMAN: Champion Jack Dupree 
was the barrelhouse piano player

254
00:13:18,331 --> 00:13:20,531
  from New Orleans who recorded 
      the original version      

255
00:13:20,600 --> 00:13:23,200
  of "The Junker Blues" in 1940 
      and had a, you know,      

256
00:13:23,269 --> 00:13:25,035
      mild success with it.     

257
00:13:25,104 --> 00:13:29,573
 And that was a song that really
     sold Fats to Lew Chudd.    

258
00:13:29,642 --> 00:13:31,308
      Lew said, "You know,      
     I gotta have this guy."    

259
00:13:31,377 --> 00:13:33,110
   And he actually signed him   
     right there on the spot    

260
00:13:33,179 --> 00:13:34,845
        that very night.        

261
00:13:34,914 --> 00:13:38,983
-DOMINO: And about a week later,
    say about 2 weeks later,    

262
00:13:39,051 --> 00:13:41,886
       we had got together      
   to record the first record,  

263
00:13:41,954 --> 00:13:44,088
        "Fat Man," 1949.        

264
00:13:44,157 --> 00:13:46,724
    -And we never looked back   
          for 25 years.         

265
00:13:46,793 --> 00:13:49,827
         [Upbeat piano]         

266
00:14:02,575 --> 00:14:06,410
  -Dave said, "We gonna record  
         'The Fat Man.'"        

267
00:14:06,479 --> 00:14:09,747
        I said, "We are?"       
       Oh, I got excited.       

268
00:14:09,816 --> 00:14:13,851
   Durin' that period of time,  
     we had a radio program,    

269
00:14:13,920 --> 00:14:16,187
         "The Fat Man."         

270
00:14:16,255 --> 00:14:17,755
  So when we got in the studio, 

271
00:14:17,824 --> 00:14:20,391
    Dave said, "This is Fats,   
          The Fat Man."         

272
00:14:20,459 --> 00:14:23,694
  I look at Dave, said, "Dave,  
  The Fat Man is a white man."  

273
00:14:23,763 --> 00:14:27,131
          -♪ They call,         
   they call me The Fat Man ♪   

274
00:14:27,200 --> 00:14:30,668
  ♪ 'Cause I weigh 200 pounds ♪ 

275
00:14:30,736 --> 00:14:33,704
 ♪ All the girls, they love me ♪

276
00:14:33,773 --> 00:14:38,475
 ♪ 'Cause I know my way around ♪

277
00:14:38,544 --> 00:14:39,577
       ♪ I was standin' ♪       

278
00:14:39,645 --> 00:14:42,313
♪ I was standin' on the corner ♪

279
00:14:42,381 --> 00:14:46,050
    ♪ Of Rampart and Canal ♪    

280
00:14:46,118 --> 00:14:49,019
  ♪ I was watchin', watchin' ♪  

281
00:14:49,088 --> 00:14:51,322
♪ Watchin' all the Creole gals ♪

282
00:14:53,993 --> 00:14:57,728
          [Vocalizing]          

283
00:14:57,797 --> 00:15:00,698
    -"Fat Man," the first hit   
   that he -- hit that he had,  

284
00:15:00,766 --> 00:15:05,603
  the first record in 1949, was 
 basically "The Junker's Blues."

285
00:15:05,671 --> 00:15:07,104
         And he told me         
       this the other day.      

286
00:15:07,173 --> 00:15:08,339
      He said, I asked him      
      about "The Fat Man. "     

287
00:15:08,407 --> 00:15:09,540
       He said, "It's just      
       The Junker's Blues.      

288
00:15:09,609 --> 00:15:10,975
     I just changed it to...    

289
00:15:11,043 --> 00:15:13,077
  From 'they call me a junker,' 
              to --             

290
00:15:13,145 --> 00:15:14,912
to, 'they call me The Fat Man'."

291
00:15:14,981 --> 00:15:18,182
               ♪♪               

292
00:15:18,250 --> 00:15:21,752
         -Fats played it        
      as if it was his own.     

293
00:15:21,821 --> 00:15:24,922
        It was very final       
        when Fats played.       

294
00:15:24,991 --> 00:15:27,257
     If you had never heard     
  whoever played the original,  

295
00:15:27,326 --> 00:15:30,361
   if you heard Fats Domino's   
    version, that was enough.   

296
00:15:30,429 --> 00:15:32,596
You can just take it from there.

297
00:15:32,665 --> 00:15:35,666
               ♪♪               

298
00:15:39,839 --> 00:15:41,672
        -So I would say,        
    "What we gonna call him?"   

299
00:15:41,741 --> 00:15:43,641
         I said, "Hell,         
   we gonna call him Fat Man."  

300
00:15:43,709 --> 00:15:48,012
               ♪♪               

301
00:15:48,080 --> 00:15:50,147
    As soon as they heard it,   
          that was it.          

302
00:15:50,216 --> 00:15:53,217
               ♪♪               

303
00:16:01,927 --> 00:16:05,796
     ♪ I'm goin', I'm goin',    
          goin' away ♪          

304
00:16:05,865 --> 00:16:10,000
         ♪ And then I'm         
     goin', goin' to stay ♪     

305
00:16:10,069 --> 00:16:12,503
 ♪ 'Cause women and a bad life ♪

306
00:16:12,571 --> 00:16:14,638
       ♪ They're carryin'       
        this soul away ♪        

307
00:16:20,146 --> 00:16:23,647
  -NARRATOR: With "The Fat Man" 
      rising to number one      

308
00:16:23,716 --> 00:16:27,217
   in the February 1950 rhythm  
        and blues charts,       

309
00:16:27,286 --> 00:16:30,621
 Lew Chudd's hunch had paid off.

310
00:16:30,689 --> 00:16:35,092
   He quickly reassembled Fats  
 with Dave Bartholomew and band 

311
00:16:35,161 --> 00:16:36,427
     for additional sessions    

312
00:16:36,495 --> 00:16:40,397
       at Cosimo Matassa's      
     Rampart Street studio.     

313
00:16:40,466 --> 00:16:45,803
 Cosimo's J&M Music Shop was the
  only recording studio in town 

314
00:16:45,871 --> 00:16:48,672
    and was quickly becoming    
    the Mecca for record men    

315
00:16:48,741 --> 00:16:50,140
      looking to cash in on     

316
00:16:50,209 --> 00:16:53,343
         the New Orleans        
     rhythm and blues sound.    

317
00:16:53,412 --> 00:16:57,147
  And Dave Bartholomew's little 
 orchestra became the house band

318
00:16:57,216 --> 00:17:01,885
backing nearly every performance
         recorded there.        

319
00:17:01,954 --> 00:17:05,022
     -New Orleans produces a    
 disproportionately large amount

320
00:17:05,090 --> 00:17:06,423
     of talented musicians.     

321
00:17:06,492 --> 00:17:09,393
     And it really comes up     
     with the raw material.     

322
00:17:09,462 --> 00:17:10,494
    -MAN: It's the only place   
          in the world          

323
00:17:10,563 --> 00:17:12,996
        where everybody,        
      even white listeners,     

324
00:17:13,065 --> 00:17:16,600
  clap on two and four instead  
        of one and three.       

325
00:17:16,669 --> 00:17:18,702
   Right away, you can tell if  
a white dude's from New Orleans,

326
00:17:18,771 --> 00:17:20,237
  man, when you hear him clap.  

327
00:17:20,306 --> 00:17:22,206
        He's on the beat.       

328
00:17:22,274 --> 00:17:23,407
          And that's --         
       that's kind of, uh,      

329
00:17:23,475 --> 00:17:26,076
      a -- a natural thing      
    with New Orleans people.    

330
00:17:26,145 --> 00:17:27,344
   You got kids in the street,  

331
00:17:27,413 --> 00:17:29,880
  man... It's a lot of talent,  
           musically,           

332
00:17:29,949 --> 00:17:32,382
 if you stand on a certain way. 

333
00:17:32,451 --> 00:17:33,917
    Well, look at the history   
          of the town.          

334
00:17:33,986 --> 00:17:35,252
   There's always been music.   

335
00:17:35,321 --> 00:17:37,454
  That's maybe why you're born  
        with a lot of it        

336
00:17:37,523 --> 00:17:39,189
        instilled in you.       

337
00:17:39,258 --> 00:17:41,859
 -You can call it the big beat, 
 the sweet beat whatever it is. 

338
00:17:41,927 --> 00:17:44,161
  But New Orleans got the beat. 

339
00:17:44,230 --> 00:17:46,530
     -There have always been    
      gigs in New Orleans.      

340
00:17:46,599 --> 00:17:48,665
       There's only really      
  a few periods in the history  

341
00:17:48,734 --> 00:17:50,167
         of New Orleans         
    in the 20th century where   

342
00:17:50,236 --> 00:17:52,870
 there's been a really thriving 
        recording scene.        

343
00:17:52,938 --> 00:17:54,872
        And, um, the fact       

344
00:17:54,940 --> 00:17:57,975
  that there was is largely due 
       to Dave Bartholomew      

345
00:17:58,043 --> 00:17:59,910
       and Cosimo Matassa.      

346
00:17:59,979 --> 00:18:04,181
               ♪♪               

347
00:18:04,250 --> 00:18:06,650
   -TOUSSAINT: Cosimo Matassa   
      and Dave Bartholomew      

348
00:18:06,719 --> 00:18:08,318
   put New Orleans on the map.  

349
00:18:08,387 --> 00:18:11,655
     -The room was 15-by-16.    

350
00:18:11,724 --> 00:18:14,524
   I started recording direct   
         to disk, which,        

351
00:18:14,593 --> 00:18:17,160
        uh, had a couple        
   of good features about it.   

352
00:18:17,229 --> 00:18:19,563
         For one thing,         
   you didn't do any editing.   

353
00:18:19,632 --> 00:18:22,132
   You didn't do any pickups.   
 You didn't do any overdubbing. 

354
00:18:22,201 --> 00:18:23,967
    You played the damn thing   
     from beginning to end.     

355
00:18:24,036 --> 00:18:27,104
      And -- and that made      
        for performance.        

356
00:18:27,172 --> 00:18:29,740
   And I think that helped me.  

357
00:18:29,808 --> 00:18:32,709
   I started on the fact that   
  everybody performed together  

358
00:18:32,778 --> 00:18:34,011
        beginning to end.       

359
00:18:34,079 --> 00:18:35,412
        Had to be right.        

360
00:18:35,481 --> 00:18:37,214
      I always, 'til today,     

361
00:18:37,283 --> 00:18:40,651
       thought that my job      
       was to put on disk       

362
00:18:40,719 --> 00:18:43,186
     what was happening out     
         in the studio.         

363
00:18:43,255 --> 00:18:46,490
 It was OJT, as Dave told me -- 
     "on the job training."     

364
00:18:46,558 --> 00:18:48,825
    -Imperial wanted us to go   
            on a tour           

365
00:18:48,894 --> 00:18:50,494
    after Fats' first record,   

366
00:18:50,562 --> 00:18:53,697
   which was "Fat Man Blues."   

367
00:18:53,766 --> 00:18:56,366
         The other side         
    was "Detroit City Blues."   

368
00:18:56,435 --> 00:18:57,601
        We had 3 days...        

369
00:18:57,670 --> 00:19:00,237
      It was late startin'      
        this tour 'cause        

370
00:19:00,305 --> 00:19:03,073
   Fats would hide every time   
  we go to look for him 'cause  

371
00:19:03,142 --> 00:19:04,307
he was afraid to go on the tour.

372
00:19:04,376 --> 00:19:05,542
   He was, you know, shook up.  

373
00:19:05,611 --> 00:19:07,744
           First time           
   he'd ever went on any tour.  

374
00:19:07,813 --> 00:19:12,149
  And we -- we got to go on --  
     go with us on the trip     

375
00:19:12,217 --> 00:19:14,618
     was Professor Longhair.    

376
00:19:14,687 --> 00:19:16,286
         -I got nothin'         
       but stars with me:       

377
00:19:16,355 --> 00:19:21,458
 Lee Allen, Professor Longhair, 

378
00:19:21,527 --> 00:19:27,297
  Fat Domino, Dave Bartholomew, 
   Bob Foreman, Frank Fields.   

379
00:19:28,167 --> 00:19:30,834
    We're playin' in a dump.    

380
00:19:30,903 --> 00:19:32,402
        At 11:30, 12:00,        

381
00:19:32,471 --> 00:19:35,705
 I said, "Wasn't he supposed to 
    pay me at intermission?"    

382
00:19:35,774 --> 00:19:38,041
    Earl Palmer say, "I seen    
   that man go out the door."   

383
00:19:38,110 --> 00:19:41,511
  I said, "Well, he goin' home  
       to get the money."       

384
00:19:41,580 --> 00:19:44,147
       That been 40 years.      
     He ain't come back yet.    

385
00:19:44,216 --> 00:19:45,649
            [Laughs]            

386
00:19:45,717 --> 00:19:48,618
               ♪♪               

387
00:20:08,273 --> 00:20:10,707
           [Whistling]          

388
00:20:35,100 --> 00:20:38,902
           -NARRATOR:           
     Between 1950 and 1955,     

389
00:20:38,971 --> 00:20:42,539
  Fats recorded a steady stream 
     of singles for Imperial    

390
00:20:42,608 --> 00:20:46,977
 with many of them charting high
       in the R&B charts.       

391
00:20:47,045 --> 00:20:49,946
       Things were buzzing      
       at Cosimo's studio.      

392
00:20:50,015 --> 00:20:51,715
      And Dave Bartholomew      

393
00:20:51,783 --> 00:20:54,684
        was the go-to guy       
    for all the record labels   

394
00:20:54,753 --> 00:20:56,453
        wishing to record       
         in New Orleans.        

395
00:20:56,522 --> 00:20:59,322
      ♪ Well, I'm goin' to      
          New Orleans ♪         

396
00:20:59,391 --> 00:21:04,461
       ♪ I'm goin' to see       
        the Mardi Gras ♪        

397
00:21:04,530 --> 00:21:07,130
      ♪ Well, I'm goin' to      
          New Orleans ♪         

398
00:21:07,199 --> 00:21:12,135
       ♪ I'm goin' to see       
        the Mardi Gras ♪        

399
00:21:12,204 --> 00:21:15,005
  ♪ When I get to New Orleans ♪ 

400
00:21:15,073 --> 00:21:17,340
        ♪ I want to know        
      what's carnival for ♪     

401
00:21:20,212 --> 00:21:24,147
           [Whistling]          

402
00:21:24,216 --> 00:21:26,149
           -NARRATOR:           
    He produced the sessions,   

403
00:21:26,218 --> 00:21:28,051
     wrote the arrangements,    

404
00:21:28,120 --> 00:21:32,022
        and used his band       
     to back the performers.    

405
00:21:32,090 --> 00:21:35,425
   -He was the man number one.  

406
00:21:35,494 --> 00:21:38,929
         He was the boss        
       with the hot sauce.      

407
00:21:38,997 --> 00:21:41,097
     MATASSA: We didn't call    
   him The Chief for nothin'.   

408
00:21:41,166 --> 00:21:42,432
        He was the chief.       

409
00:21:42,501 --> 00:21:44,234
       He kept us focused,      

410
00:21:44,303 --> 00:21:46,736
     and particularly people    
    like Fats he kept focused   

411
00:21:46,805 --> 00:21:49,105
  because Fats tended to doodle 
    and ramble and -- and --    

412
00:21:49,174 --> 00:21:50,540
     and that sort of thing.    

413
00:21:50,609 --> 00:21:51,808
          I think, uh,          

414
00:21:51,877 --> 00:21:53,543
         without a Dave,        
there might not have been a Fats

415
00:21:53,612 --> 00:21:56,546
  in the national sense of it.  

416
00:21:58,817 --> 00:22:01,751
     [Cheering and applause]    

417
00:22:01,820 --> 00:22:03,553
       -DOMINO: Thank you.      

418
00:22:03,622 --> 00:22:06,790
   -COLEMAN: Fats showed up in  
his Cadillac at Cosimo's studio.

419
00:22:06,858 --> 00:22:09,959
 And Dave was cutting a session 
        with Lloyd Price.       

420
00:22:10,028 --> 00:22:13,663
And the piano player at the time
        in Dave's band --       

421
00:22:13,732 --> 00:22:15,398
         I think it was         
      Salvador Doucette --      

422
00:22:15,467 --> 00:22:18,234
         was not really         
 cutting the triplets too well. 

423
00:22:18,303 --> 00:22:22,672
   And so Fats was the perfect  
     answer to that problem.    

424
00:22:22,741 --> 00:22:24,808
        And he asked Fats       
       if he would sit in.      

425
00:22:24,876 --> 00:22:27,077
           And then he          
played that amazing introduction

426
00:22:27,145 --> 00:22:29,346
     to "Lawdy Miss Clawdy."    

427
00:22:29,414 --> 00:22:33,049
               ♪♪               

428
00:22:33,118 --> 00:22:34,751
      And then the triplets     

429
00:22:34,820 --> 00:22:36,486
      and then a -- a solo      
         in the middle.         

430
00:22:36,555 --> 00:22:39,155
  And it... "Lawdy Miss Clawdy" 
     became the biggest hit     

431
00:22:39,224 --> 00:22:41,725
 of the year and knocked his own
    number one, "Goin' Home,"   

432
00:22:41,793 --> 00:22:44,094
       out of the charts.       

433
00:22:44,162 --> 00:22:48,498
            [Playing]           

434
00:23:00,078 --> 00:23:01,277
 -I think I played on that one. 

435
00:23:01,346 --> 00:23:02,212
      -MAN: Yeah, you did.      
           -MAN: Yeah.          

436
00:23:02,280 --> 00:23:04,447
         -Yeah. You did.        

437
00:23:04,516 --> 00:23:06,216
      -MAN: And here it is,     

438
00:23:06,284 --> 00:23:08,952
          "Alan Freed's         
      Rock 'n' Roll Party."     

439
00:23:09,020 --> 00:23:11,821
    And here he is in person:   
           Alan Freed.          

440
00:23:11,890 --> 00:23:14,524
      [Cheers and applause]     

441
00:23:14,593 --> 00:23:16,159
       -Hello, everybody.       
         How are y'all?         

442
00:23:16,228 --> 00:23:18,361
  Welcome to our rock 'n' roll  
        jubilee of stars.       

443
00:23:18,430 --> 00:23:19,929
    And here we go to rockin'   

444
00:23:19,998 --> 00:23:22,165
     with wailin' tenorman,     
         Freddy Mitchell        

445
00:23:22,234 --> 00:23:23,666
  and the rock 'n' roll boogie! 

446
00:23:23,735 --> 00:23:25,135
           Here we go.          

447
00:23:25,203 --> 00:23:27,737
    -COLEMAN: Alan Freed had    
     actually started using     

448
00:23:27,806 --> 00:23:30,273
   the phrase "rock 'n' roll"   
       at the end of 1954.      

449
00:23:30,342 --> 00:23:33,643
  And the first ever so-called  
      rock 'n' roll concert     

450
00:23:33,712 --> 00:23:36,546
    was his show in New York,   
         January of '55.        

