       There's been riots.      

838
00:44:48,484 --> 00:44:50,551
        It's been banned        
in certain parts of this country

839
00:44:50,620 --> 00:44:51,652
           and abroad.          

840
00:44:51,721 --> 00:44:53,387
You know of any reason for that?

841
00:44:53,456 --> 00:44:55,189
    -Well, as far as I know,    

842
00:44:55,258 --> 00:44:57,792
    music make people happy.    
    I know it make me happy.    

843
00:44:57,860 --> 00:44:59,360
  -COMO: You wouldn't blame it  
        on rock 'n' roll.       

844
00:44:59,429 --> 00:45:00,895
          -No, indeed.          

845
00:45:00,963 --> 00:45:02,263
      -What happened up in      
          Rhode Island          

846
00:45:02,331 --> 00:45:04,165
    where you where playin'?    
 -Well, you know how it is when 

847
00:45:04,233 --> 00:45:05,433
      the Navy and Marines      
          get together.         

848
00:45:05,501 --> 00:45:06,434
        -You don't think        
        it was the music?       

849
00:45:06,502 --> 00:45:08,102
        -No, couldn't be.       

850
00:45:08,171 --> 00:45:11,172
   -NARRATOR: Life on the road  
     for an African-American    

851
00:45:11,240 --> 00:45:14,542
    rock 'n' roll band, even    
 the country's most popular one,

852
00:45:14,610 --> 00:45:17,378
        was mired in the        
     pre-Civil Rights mores     

853
00:45:17,447 --> 00:45:20,014
           of the day.          

854
00:45:20,083 --> 00:45:24,318
   -DOMINO: Sometimes we used   
  to go up 100 mile out the way 

855
00:45:24,387 --> 00:45:26,454
    to get a place to sleep.    

856
00:45:26,522 --> 00:45:30,558
   -It was tough. We stayed in  
   little, small-like hotels.   

857
00:45:30,626 --> 00:45:35,663
  We didn't have the privilege  
   and the -- the restaurants.  

858
00:45:35,731 --> 00:45:39,266
   I started drivin' the bus.   

859
00:45:39,335 --> 00:45:41,235
         And I would go         
     into these restaurants     

860
00:45:41,304 --> 00:45:43,704
         or these places        
  and sort of help integration  

861
00:45:43,773 --> 00:45:46,841
 along to push things, you know?

862
00:45:46,909 --> 00:45:49,009
       And when the hotels      
  first integrated, that was -- 

863
00:45:49,078 --> 00:45:50,578
  I was the first ones in them. 

864
00:45:50,646 --> 00:45:54,248
  -Well, I think there is, uh,  
  no doubt about the fact that, 

865
00:45:54,317 --> 00:45:58,752
          uh, the Negro         
   is more determined now than  

866
00:45:58,821 --> 00:46:00,254
     ever before to be free.    

867
00:46:00,323 --> 00:46:04,158
      I think that there is     
          a discontent          

868
00:46:04,227 --> 00:46:07,761
     in the Negro community,    
a frustration and an impatience,

869
00:46:07,830 --> 00:46:10,731
  if we can use that word, uh,  

870
00:46:10,800 --> 00:46:12,500
  that we haven't seen before.  

871
00:46:12,568 --> 00:46:15,936
  I've been around the country  
     for the last few days,     

872
00:46:16,005 --> 00:46:17,204
          uh, speaking.         

873
00:46:17,273 --> 00:46:20,074
        And I don't think       
       I've ever seen, uh,      

874
00:46:20,142 --> 00:46:22,209
      the Negro population      
          of our nation         

875
00:46:22,278 --> 00:46:26,480
more aroused and more determined

876
00:46:26,549 --> 00:46:29,583
          as I've seen          
   on these particular trips.   

877
00:46:29,652 --> 00:46:31,719
        -DIAMOND: Before        
 Martin Luther King got killed, 

878
00:46:31,787 --> 00:46:34,555
   Fats was in that same hotel  
       2 weeks before then      

879
00:46:34,624 --> 00:46:37,825
       playin' for the --       
   the garbage workers there.   

880
00:46:37,894 --> 00:46:40,694
        He'd bring the --       
  the workers together when --  

881
00:46:40,763 --> 00:46:43,364
       whenever he'd play,      
        white and black.        

882
00:46:43,432 --> 00:46:45,733
 It's somethin' about his person

883
00:46:45,801 --> 00:46:47,801
         that draw a lot        
     of people in, you know.    

884
00:46:47,870 --> 00:46:52,006
  -MAN: Once it was recognized, 
        once it accepted,       

885
00:46:52,074 --> 00:46:55,976
  and once the -- the audience, 
           the people           

886
00:46:56,045 --> 00:46:57,578
   started wantin' this music,  

887
00:46:57,647 --> 00:46:59,446
        there was nothin'       
     that the radio stations    

888
00:46:59,515 --> 00:47:01,615
 or television can do about it. 

889
00:47:01,684 --> 00:47:04,084
     They had to accept it.     

890
00:47:04,153 --> 00:47:06,720
     -COLEMAN: So there was     
      this historic moment      

891
00:47:06,789 --> 00:47:08,088
       in American history      

892
00:47:08,157 --> 00:47:10,391
       that -- that things      
  were kind of coming together. 

893
00:47:10,459 --> 00:47:12,860
     And people don't really    
      credit rock 'n' roll      

894
00:47:12,928 --> 00:47:14,361
    with integrating America.   

895
00:47:14,430 --> 00:47:17,598
       But it really did.       

896
00:47:17,667 --> 00:47:21,068
 -NARRATOR: Constantly far away 
     from his loving family     

897
00:47:21,137 --> 00:47:23,704
    and his Ninth Ward home,    

898
00:47:23,773 --> 00:47:27,608
        life on the road        
 was beginning to take its toll.

899
00:47:27,677 --> 00:47:29,043
        -DOMINO: Anybody,       
   when you first leave home,   

900
00:47:29,111 --> 00:47:30,411
     especially New Orleans,    

901
00:47:30,479 --> 00:47:32,079
     you still got your home    
          on your mind.         

